<div id="review_435388001" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/435388001" />
    <a title="MsBDiamondDiva1" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3905386-msbdiamonddiva1"><img alt="MsBDiamondDiva1" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442350667p2/3905386.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/435388001?book_show_action=true">Oct 16, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="MsBDiamondDiva1" class="user" itemprop="url" name="MsBDiamondDiva1" href="/user/show/3905386-msbdiamonddiva1">MsBDiamondDiva1</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3905386-msbdiamonddiva1?shelf=trash-books">trash-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3905386-msbdiamonddiva1?shelf=zombies">zombies</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer435388001" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8335178125303305001">Thanks to the blue sky I have finished this piece of junk!!! I am so sorry, I just could not like this story as much as I tried; this zombie story fall flat!!! Why are there so many good reviews on this book? <br/> I mean here is the main reason:<br/><br/>1.	The characters know that a bite, blood, fluid or scratch would get them infected-but no one thinks to put on leather, extra layers or anything to protect their skin!!! So, they were basically saying- &quot;Look at me zombie; I am a walking fried chicken leg.&quot;<br/><br/>2.</span>
  <span id="freeText8335178125303305001" style="display:none">Thanks to the blue sky I have finished this piece of junk!!! I am so sorry, I just could not like this story as much as I tried; this zombie story fall flat!!! Why are there so many good reviews on this book? <br /> I mean here is the main reason:<br /><br />1.	The characters know that a bite, blood, fluid or scratch would get them infected-but no one thinks to put on leather, extra layers or anything to protect their skin!!! So, they were basically saying- "Look at me zombie; I am a walking fried chicken leg."<br /><br />2.	Sherman doesn’t make good decision, but yet the author has you under the impression that he is a wise guy. Well, he isn’t too smart walking into a silent town; knowing damn well that the outbreak has been spreading at a rapid pace for the last week. <br /><br />3.	The characters language, mostly Brewster is so annoying that I had to stop reading several times to relax my jaw muscle from clenching so hard. This guy is super annoying and should have got killed off soon. He put a lot of people in danger with his stupid ass suggestions to Sherman. And for Sherman to even consider this loser advice is beyond me. <br /><br />4.	The author kills off character that are likable and that you want to live to fight another day. <br /><br />5.	Why keep making body shoots? When all you have to do is make one good head shot!!! <br /><br />6.	The over use of the military terms and military language is a major turn off. Just think about it, if an outbreak really happened; the 1st place to go would be the areas most crowded and therefore the authors logic of the military lasting as long as it has in this book in illogical. <br /><br />Therefore, this book in one of the waste books I have ever read:-(<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="8335178125303305001" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


