<div id="review_465148926" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/465148926" />
    <a title="Tracy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2932070-tracy"><img alt="Tracy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1270004734p2/2932070.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/465148926?book_show_action=true">Nov 27, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tracy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tracy" href="/user/show/2932070-tracy">Tracy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer465148926" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10372441414148672858">Woohoo! Finally got a new computer so I can start reviewing books again. And why not start out with a zombie book?<br/><br/>OK, so here&apos;s the thing about the zombie apocalypse: I have pretty much decided I am a goner when it happens. I can&apos;t shoot a gun, or a bow. I can&apos;t change a tire, especially if there were a group of the undead approaching. I don&apos;t have more than a few cans of soup and some bottles stored in my basement. (Yowza! I could get by for a week at least!) Heck, I couldn&apos;t even survive the R</span>
  <span id="freeText10372441414148672858" style="display:none">Woohoo! Finally got a new computer so I can start reviewing books again. And why not start out with a zombie book?<br /><br />OK, so here's the thing about the zombie apocalypse: I have pretty much decided I am a goner when it happens. I can't shoot a gun, or a bow. I can't change a tire, especially if there were a group of the undead approaching. I don't have more than a few cans of soup and some bottles stored in my basement. (Yowza! I could get by for a week at least!) Heck, I couldn't even survive the Run for Your Lives race with my flags intact...and that was with zombies giving an exhausted girl some loving and letting me pass without taking my flag.<br /><br />So, this book just added to my knowledge of exactly why I won't survive...1) I am not in the army. 2) I am not a RED Cross volunteer somewhere in the Middle East with a vast array of medical knowledge. 3) I do not know how I would contact the Navy to come and rescue me from some zombie infested port city and for that matter I would not have known that some piers can be unstrapped from their docks, thereby making them floats. 4) I don't know a retired, former Army mechanic who lives on a small island in the middle of nowhere who would be able to fix my giant Navy boat when one of the engines got (oops!) accidentally shot.<br /><br />All of these things happen in this book and even half of the people who DID know these things bite it anyway. Or, well, the zombies bite them anyway. So, pretty cheesy book, but it was fun and it did make me want to read the next in the trilogy. (Again with the trilogies, people??)<br /><br />But, yeah, I'm a goner.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10372441414148672858" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


