  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_52532388" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/52532388" />
    <a title="Joe" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/151188-joe"><img alt="Joe" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1188216289p2/151188.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/52532388?book_show_action=true">Apr 13, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joe" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joe" href="/user/show/151188-joe">Joe</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer52532388" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8122694201968402603">_Plague of the Dead_ is, put simply, a zombie outbreak novel similar in many ways to Max Brooks&apos; spectacular _World War Z_. (WWZ is told in a series of interviews while _Plague_ follows a traditional narrative format, but the manner in which the plague spreads and the military&apos;s fruitless efforts to contain it are similar.)<br/>_Plague_ has some strong characters and some pretty awesome moments. You got to love a book where a soldier, already bitten and therefore terminal, hangs on to his grenade unt</span>
  <span id="freeText8122694201968402603" style="display:none">_Plague of the Dead_ is, put simply, a zombie outbreak novel similar in many ways to Max Brooks' spectacular _World War Z_. (WWZ is told in a series of interviews while _Plague_ follows a traditional narrative format, but the manner in which the plague spreads and the military's fruitless efforts to contain it are similar.)<br />_Plague_ has some strong characters and some pretty awesome moments. You got to love a book where a soldier, already bitten and therefore terminal, hangs on to his grenade until the last moment, laughing maniacally while hordes of zombies pile on...<br />_Plague_'s sequel, _Thunder and Ashes_ is more of the same, but even better. No lavish, majestic prose here, just some lean action-packed narrative.<br />My only criticism of this book, an attack I would also levy at many other novels, is that the characters facing this kind of unspeakable horror never seem scared enough. If the world truly was being overrun by the walking dead and several hundred were shambling toward you, there is no way you'd be cracking jokes or doing much more than crying and possibly even wetting yourself. Right? But then, I'm not a writer. Maybe it is hard to make a novel work when the characters are spending the whole book crying and wetting themselves...</span>
  <a data-text-id="8122694201968402603" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

